- `add(T item)`: Adds an item to the box.
- `remove()`: Removes and returns the last item added to the box. If the box is empty, it throws a `NoSuchElementException`.
- `peek()`: Returns the last item added to the box without removing it. If the box is empty, it throws a `NoSuchElementException`.
- `isEmpty()`: Returns true if the box is empty, false otherwise.
- `size()`: Returns the number of items in the box.

You should write tests to ensure that all these methods work correctly, including edge cases like removing from an empty box or peeking at an empty box.

```java
generic class Box<T> {
    private List<T> items = new ArrayList<>();

    public void add(T item) {
        items.add(item);
    }

    public T remove() {
        if (items.isEmpty()) {
            throw new NoSuchElementException("Box is empty");
        }
        return items.remove(items.size() - 1);
    }

    public T peek() {
        if (items.isEmpty()) {
            throw new NoSuchElementException("Box is empty");
        }
        return items.get(items.size() - 1);
    }

    public boolean isEmpty() {
        return items.isEmpty();
    }

    public int size() {
        return items.size();
    }
}
```

